ve\n|\nWhen you lose everything, you are free. You become a receiver.\n\n- Ashlecka\n|\nIf you show someone something you've written, you give them a sharpened stake, lie down in your coffin, and say, ‘When you’re ready’.\n\n- David Mitchell, Black Swan Green\n|\nKeep on reading, thinking, doing and writing! Words keep introducing their friends to you.\n\n- Toba Beta, My Ancestor Was an Ancient Astronaut\n|\n…the worst thing said about him is that he was 'uncurious.\n\n- Yvon Chouinard, Let My People Go Surfing: The Education of a Reluctant Businessman\n|\nNo, but I do read a lot. I love to read. I could read for days and never stop. I use to be such a bookworm. I would barely look up to notice much of anything.\n\n- Jennifer Loren, The Devil's Eyes\n|\nAll religions are equally sublime to the ignorant, useful to the politician, and ridiculous to the philosopher.\n\n- Titus Lucretius Carus, On the Nature of Things: de Rerum Natura\n|\nOne ought, every day at least, to hear a little song, read a good poem, see a fine picture, and, if it were possible, to speak a few reasonable words.\n\n- Johann Wolfgang von Goethe, Wilhelm Meister's Apprenticeship\n|\nWhen I type a title page, I hold it and I look at it and I think, I just need four thousand sentences to go with this and I’ll have a book.\n\n- Betsy Byars, The Moon and I\n|\nAll are lunatics, but he who can analyze his delusion is called a philosopher.\n\n- Ambrose Bierce, The Collected Writings Of Ambrose Bierce\n|\nThat's the thing about lessons, you always learn them when you don't expect them or want them.\n\n- Cecelia Ahern, If You Could See Me Now\n|\nYou were you,and I was I;we were twobefore our time.I was yoursbefore I knew,and you have always been mine too.\n\n- Lang Leav, Love & Misadventure\n|\nStrange. Half my years afraid of life. The other half, afraid of death. Always some kind of afraid.\n\n- Ray Bradbury, Bradbury Stories: 100 of His Most Celebrated Tales\n|\nMay your choices reflect your hopes, not your fears.\n\n- Nelson\n|\nEven if such beauty wasn't meant to be in a world so fallen as ours, that didn't take away from its beauty. It only made it more beautiful.\n\n- Kyle West, The Wasteland Chronicles: Omnibus Edition\n|\nKnowledge is responsibility, which is why people resist knowledge.\n\n- Stefan\n|\nIf you haven't been in a war and are wondering how long it takes to get used to losing everything you think you need or love, I can tell you the answer is no time at all.\n\n- Meg Rosoff, How I Live Now\n|\nExcept our own thoughts, there is nothing absolutely in our power.\n\n- René\n|\nIn the end, it is our defiance that redeems us. If wolves had a religion – if there was a religion of the wolf – that it is what it would tell us.\n\n- Mark Rowlands, The Philosopher and the Wolf: Lessons from the Wild on Love, Death, and Happiness\n|\nAfter all these years, I feel so free. Who knows where I might fly?\n\n- Kim Edwards, The Memory Keeper's Daughter\n|\nDo not imagine that mathematics is hard and crabbed, and repulsive to common sense. It is merely the etherealization of common sense.\n\n- William Thomson, 1st Baron Kelvin\n|\nMake mistakes, a thousand of them because we are only humans.Never repeat your mistakes because we are humans.\n\n- Akash Lakhotia, World Hypnotized: Making of the Fuhrer\n|\nThere is a warin your nameI have martyred yousold you to freedomoh, Freedom\n\n- Bänoo Zan, Songs of Exile\n|\nYoga not only allows you to learn to control your breathing, but it ultimately enhances your abilities to harmonize your thoughts and enhances your inner beauty.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nSoy el desesperado, la palabra sin ecos, el que lo perdiò todo, y el que todo lo tuvo.\n\n- Pablo Neruda, Veinte Poemas de Amor y una Canción Desesperada\n|\nDon’t fellowship with people around you alone, explore and reach out to more people\n\n- Sunday\n|\nInstead of exchanging your life for some coins and some pennies, you could actually take charge of your life right now. You 