m, it’s absolute unfreedom.\n\n- Arthur\n|\nDeath is an illusion, Love is not!\n\n- Tapan Ghosh, Faceless The Only Way Out\n|\nMost of all I remember that what begins with drums and fife, flags and bunting, becomes too swiftly a long and grey winter of the spirit.\n\n- Helen Simonson, The Summer Before the War\n|\nWhen the mind is free, magic happens.\n\n- C.G.\n|\nBermimpilah, karena Tuhan akan memeluk mimpi-mimpi itu.\n\n- Andrea Hirata, Sang Pemimpi\n|\nOne changes, as a writer, fairly quickly; what you wrote six months or a year ago might not sound right anymore.\n\n- Keith\n|\nI personally find that for domestic purposes, the Trivial Pursuit system works better than Dewey.\n\n- Nick Hornby, The Polysyllabic Spree\n|\nJust when you think you have it all figured out, an epiphany arrives at the higher level of one's consciousness.\n\n- Terry\n|\nTrouble has no necessary connection with discouragement --discouragement has a germ of its own, as different from trouble as arthritis is different from a stiff joint.\n\n- F. Scott Fitzgerald, The Crack-Up\n|\nCaius was one of those who gloried in his ignorance, called his lack of letters purity, scorned any subtlety of thought or expression. A man for his time, indeed.\n\n- Iain Pears, The Dream of Scipio\n|\nRead, re-read and un-read!\n\n- Lailah Gifty Akita, Think Great: Be Great!\n|\nFalsity consists in the privation of knowledge, which inadequate, fragmentary, or confused ideas involve.\n\n- Baruch Spinoza, Ethics\n|\nWe cannot face up to what lies ahead, without facing up to what lies within.\n\n- Eleesha\n|\nIt all goes away. Eventually, everything goes away.\n\n- Elizabeth Gilbert, Eat, Pray, Love\n|\nFaith isn't absence of doubt. It's belief without proof, not without question.\n\n- Rosemary Clement-Moore, Hell Week\n|\nAn apple tree is just like a person. In order to thrive, it needs companionship that's similar to it in some ways, but quite different than others.\n\n- Jeffrey Stepakoff, The Orchard\n|\nKita tid